  "prompt": "What is the transpose of a matrix ?",
  "response": "The transpose of a matrix is obtained by flipping the matrix over its diagonal, which essentially switches the matrix's rows with its columns. If you have a matrix \\(A\\) with elements \\(a_{ij}\\) (where \\(i\\) is the row index and \\(j\\) is the column index), the transpose of \\(A\\), denoted \\(A^T\\) or \\(A'\\), is a new matrix whose elements are \\(a_{ji}\\).\n\nFor example, consider the following matrix \\(A\\):\n\n\\[ A = \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 2 & 3 \\\\ 4 & 5 & 6 \\end{pmatrix} \\]\n\nThe transpose of \\(A\\), denoted \\(A^T\\), would be:\n\n\\[ A^T = \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 4 \\\\ 2 & 5 \\\\ 3 & 6 \\end{pmatrix} \\]\n\nIn this new matrix, the element originally in the \\(i\\)-th row and \\(j\\)-th column of matrix \\(A\\) is now in the \\(j\\)-th row and \\(i\\)-th column of the transposed matrix \\(A^T\\).",
